{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti 4.212 and 4.217** (in Chapter 5 of this edition) provide clear examples of *smṛti* rules hinging on *aśauca* (ritual impurity, particularly *jātyaśauca* from birth and *mṛtyuśauca* from death). A twice-born man (i.e., Brahmin, Kṣatriya, or Vaiśya) must avoid \"food from a house under impurity from childbirth\" (jātyaśauca) and \"food offered to a corpse before the ten days of impurity are over\" (mṛtyuśauca).[^1][^2] These periods of seclusion—typically 10 days for death of close kin, varying by relation and caste, and shorter for birth—bar the affected household from hosting guests, preparing oblations, or offering food, as the impurity transmits ritually.[^3]\n\nEnglish \"impurity\" misleads because it connotes moral corruption, ethical stain, or physical filth (e.g., adulterated water or unclean hands), implying fault, contagion, or hygiene. *Aśauca*, however, is an automatic, non-moral ritual incapacity triggered by natural life events (birth/death in the family), not personal sin or dirt. It enforces social distance for purity in rites, ends via fixed time/baths/mantras, and underscores hierarchy—e.g., Brahmins observe longer than Śūdras. An English-only reader might dismiss it as primitive sanitation, overlooking its role in maintaining *varṇa*-dharma and cosmic order.\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 5, p-7851cc](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-7851cc).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 5, p-15103f](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-15103f).\n\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, [Chapter 5](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/). The broader context lists forbidden foods, emphasizing ritual eligibility over physical cleanliness.",
